question.text: Which of the following bonds is the most polar?

explanation.concept_text: A polar bond is a covalent bond between two atoms, where the electrons that form the bond are unequally distributed. A polar bond occurs due to the difference in electronegativity between the atoms. When one atom is significantly more electronegative, it will pull the bonding electrons more towards it, which causes the molecule to have a dipole moment where one end is slightly positive and the other end is negative. Note : Electronegativity increases as we move from left to right and from bottom to top of the periodic table, with F being the most electronegative. Given this trend, we can determine the most polar bond by inferring the largest electronegativity difference. When we do this, we determine that the O-H bond has the biggest electronegativity difference since Oxygen is much more electronegative than Hydrogen. Therefore, this results in a dipole moment, and thus a polar bond. CC By 4.0
explanation.poe_text: Option A. C-H - This bond is considered to be non-polar. Therefore, this option is incorrect. Option B. O-F - This bond is non-polar because the electronegativity of O is close to that of F, so there will not be a significant imbalance in electron distribution. Therefore, this option is incorrect. Option C. C-C - This bond is non-polar because it is a bond between the two same atoms, which means there is no difference in electronegativity. Therefore, this option is incorrect. Option D. C-N - This bond is non-polar because the electronegativity of C is close to that of N, which means there will not be a significant imbalance in electron distribution. Therefore, this option is incorrect.

question.text: Radioactive decay is the spontaneous breakdown of an atomic nucleus resulting in the release of energy and matter from the nucleus. What order kinetics does radioactive decay follow?

explanation.concept_text: Radioactive decay , is the emission of a particle or a photon that results from the spontaneous decomposition of the unstable nucleus of an atom. The rate of radioactive decay is an intrinsic property of each radioactive isotope that is independent of temperature and the chemical and physical form of the radioactive isotope. Radioactive decay is a first-order reaction because the time required for half of the nuclei in any sample of a radioactive isotope to decay is a constant, called the half-life of the isotope. Remember, the rate of reaction is proportional to the concentration in first order kinetics, as shown in the image below. In radioactive decay the number of radioactive atoms decaying per unit time is proportional to the total number of radioactive atoms present at that time. Therefore, the answer is Option B . First-order kinetics . CC By 4.0

question.text: Elements that have 7 electrons in their outermost shell and commonly form salts during chemical reactions are collectively known as

explanation.concept_text: Halogens form group 17 of the periodic table and include F, Cl, Br, I, and At. They are non-metal elements that have 7 electrons in their outermost shell and tend to be very reactive since they easily tend to accept one electron to attain a stable octet. CC By 4.0

question.text: Which of the following elements has the lowest electron affinity?

explanation.concept_text: Electron Affinity is defined as the amount of energy released or spent when an electron is added to a neutral atom or molecule in the gaseous state to form a negative ion. Electron affinity increases UPWARD for the groups and from LEFT to RIGHT across periods of the periodic table. The electron affinity trend is because as electrons are added to energy levels, they become closer to the nucleus resulting in a stronger attraction between the nucleus and its electrons. Remember that greater the distance, the less of an attraction; and therefore less energy is released when an electron is added to the outside orbital. In addition, the more valence electrons an element has, the more likely it is to gain electrons to form a stable octet. The less valence electrons an atom has, the least likely it will gain electrons. Exception: Group VIII of the periodic table (Noble gases) is quite special because they already have eight valence electrons, which fill their outer energy level. They can't accept any more electrons, therefore, the electron affinity of nobles gases is practically zero. Option E. Neon has the lowest affinity because its outermost shell is completely filled with electrons. CC By 4.0 *The trends are increasing in the direction the arrows are pointing towards.

question.text: Which of the following is true for a reaction that has a small negative ΔG value?

options.label: A.
options.text: Products will be favored at equilibrium

options.label: B.
options.text: Reactants will be favored at equilibrium

options.label: C.
options.text: No reactants will remain at equilibrium

options.label: D.
options.text: No products will remain at equilibrium

correct_answer_text: Products will be favored at equilibrium

explanation.concept_text: The Gibbs free energy (G) of a system is a measure of the amount of usable energy (energy that can do work) in a system. The change in Gibbs Free Energy (△G) is given as: △G = G products – G reactants G products = Gibbs free energy of the product G reactants = Gibbs free energy for the reactant The △G of a reaction tells us the maximum usable energy released or absorbed going from the initial reactant to the final product. This provides useful information about the reaction’s spontaneity, such as whether the reaction will proceed or not without added energy: Going back to the question, when a reaction has a small and negative △G value, it means that the reactant has slightly more free energy than the product as shown in the image below. Therefore, the reaction will be spontaneous and will favor the products of the reaction since no energy is required. Therefore, the correct answer is Option A. Products will be favored at equilibrium. CC By 4.0
explanation.poe_text: Option B. Reactants will be favored at equilibrium - This is incorrect because this would only occur when △G  > 0, in which reactants are favored when the reaction is at equilibrium. Option C. No reactants will remain at equilibrium - This is incorrect because although the reaction would be spontaneous and favors the products at equilibrium, both reactants and products would still coexist at equilibrium. Option D. No products will remain at equilibrium - This is incorrect because although the reaction would be spontaneous and favors the products at equilibrium, both reactants and products would still coexist at equilibrium. Option E. No reaction would occur - This would only occur if △G = 0, in which neither products or reactants are favored when the reaction is at equilibrium. Therefore, this option is incorrect .

explanation.concept_text: Experimental errors cause uncertainty in the data. Depending on how the error affects the certainty of the data, they can be classified into TWO categories: Since random errors cause unpredictable fluctuations, the only method to minimize the uncertainty caused by random errors is to collect more data and compute a more accurate average. Since systematic errors cause consistent fluctuations, uncertainty caused by systemic errors can be reduced through statistical analysis. question.text: At which point during a titration experiment does pH = pK a ?

explanation.concept_text: In a titration experiment, a measured amount of an acid or a base solution of a known concentration is slowly added to another solution containing a base or an acid of an unknown concentration. During this experiment, the acid or base being titrated is fully neutralized at the equivalence point. At half-equivalence point , the moles of the base added are only half the moles of acid originally present. Therefore, the concentration of the conjugate base and the remaining weak acid are the same. To further explain this, recall the Henderson-Hasselbalch equation: pH = pK a + log [Conjugate Base]/[Acid] pH = pK a + log [A - ]/[HA] In order for pH to equal pK a , the concentrations of the conjugate base and acid would have to be the same, as shown below: pH = pK a + log [1]/[1] pH = pK Refer to the image below for a visualization of this concept: CC By 4.0
explanation.poe_text: Option B. Equivalence point - At the equivalence point, moles of base = moles of acid. However, the pH will not equal the pKa. Therefore, this option is incorrect. Option C. Triple point - The triple point describes the temperature and pressure at which solid, liquid, and gas phases of a substance coexist in equilibrium. In this case, it is not relevant to pH and titration. Therefore, this option is incorrect. Option D. Second equivalence point - This usually occurs with diprotic acids or bases (can donate or accept more than one proton). E.g. at the second equivalence point, 1 mole of diprotic acid will have reacted with 2 moles of base. pH will not equal pKa at this point. Therefore, this option is incorrect. Option E. Critical point - The critical point describes the endpoint of a phase equilibrium curve. At this point, the two phases become indistinguishable. E.g. liquid-gas critical point. In this case, it is not relevant to pH and titration. Therefore, this option is incorrect.

question.text: What process occurs when the vapor pressure of a liquid equals the atmospheric pressure?

explanation.concept_text: The boiling point of a liquid is the temperature at which the vapor pressure of the liquid equals the atmospheric pressure surrounding the liquid, as shown in the image below. Boiling occurs when the vapor pressure produced as a result of heat supplied equals the surrounding pressure. The surrounding pressure could be atmospheric pressure or the total pressure of the system. When a liquid in an open container (an open system) is heated, the surrounding pressure is the atmospheric pressure. vapor starts accumulating above the container as a result of heat supplied and after some time it starts boiling it is said that the liquid has reached its boiling point because the accumulated vapor pressure is equal to the atmospheric pressure. question.text: At 37°C, which one of the following solutions produces the lowest osmotic pressure?

explanation.concept_text: Osmotic pressure is the pressure that must be applied to a prevent osmosis of a solution. It is a colligative property , meaning it depends on the concentration of solute, and not identity of the solute. The diffusion of a solvent during osmosis produces an osmotic pressure against the membrane, which is calculated for an ideal solution by the osmosis equation: π = iMRT Where, π = osmotic pressure, i = van ‘t Hoff factor, M = solute molar concentration (mol/L), R = ideal gas constant (0.0821 L·atm/mol·K), and T = solution temperature (in Kelvin) When MgSO 4 is dissolved in water, it dissociates into two ions, making the van 't Hoff factor equal to 2. A solution that has 0.40 M MgSO 4 gives a solution with an osmotic pressure expressed generally by: π = iMRT π = 2(0.40 mol • L -1 )(R)(T) = 0.80RT atm The other solutions involve compounds for which the product of the van 't Hoff factor and the molar solute concentration produce a higher osmotic pressure; therefore, the correct answer is that Option B. 0.40 M MgSO 4 exhibits the lowest osmotic pressure. Canadian DAT Pro-Tip : When solving questions like this on the Canadian DAT, do not worry about variables with decimals such as R = 0.0821. Since calculators are NOT allowed for the Canadian DAT, it is best not to fully solve equations and keep certain variables abbreviated as shown above.
explanation.poe_text: Option A. 0.90 M fructose – is incorrect because fructose dissolved in water does not dissociate (i = 1). Therefore, π = 1(0.90)RT = 0.90RT atm. Option C. 0.40 M (NH 4 ) 2 SO 4 - is incorrect because aqueous (NH 4 ) 2 SO 4 has a van 't Hoff factor of 3. Therefore, π = 3(0.40)RT = 1.2RT atm. Option D. 0.32 M Na 2 SO 4 - is incorrect because aqueous Na 2 SO 4 has a van 't Hoff factor of 3. Therefore, π = 3(0.32)RT = 0.96RT atm. Option E. 1.0 M sucrose - is incorrect because sucrose dissolved in water does not dissociate (i = 1). Therefore, π = 1(1.0)RT = 1.0RT atm.

If the amount of gas in a container is increased, the volume increases. If the amount of gas in a container is decreased, the volume decreases. This is assuming of course that the container has expandable walls. Since the relationship is directly proportional. the equation for calculations is: CC By 4.0 Therefore, the answer is Option E. Avogadro’s law since two gases of equal volumes will also have equal number of moles (number of molecules) based on this law. question.text: How many equivalent resonance structures can be drawn for the nitrate ion, NO 3 - ?

explanation.concept_text: To determine the equivalent resonance structures , we must first determine the number of valence electrons. By looking at the periodic table, we can see that nitrogen belongs to Group 5, while oxygen belongs to Group 6A. Since the group number represents the number of outermost electrons, we know that nitrogen has 5 valence electrons while oxygen has 6 valence electrons. Now that we know the number of valence electrons per element, we need to compute the total number of valence electrons: 5 + (3 × 6) = 23 electrons Note : Since the whole molecule has a -1 charge, we need to keep this into consideration as well. Therefore, the total number of valence electrons is: 23 + 1 = 24 electrons Now that we have the total valence electrons, we can draw out all the possible resonance structures of NO 3 - without violating the octet rule. By doing this, we determine that there are THREE possible resonance structures can be drawn for nitrate, NO 3 - as shown below: CC BY 4.0

question.text: Each of the following reactions has an equilibrium point that is affected by changes in pressure EXCEPT one. Which one is the EXCEPTION?

options.label: A.
options.text: Li 2 S ( aq ) + HBr ( aq ) → 2 LiBr ( aq ) + H 2 S ( g )

options.label: C.
options.text: 2 Na ( s) + Cl 2( g ) → 2 NaCl ( s )

options.label: D.
options.text: C ( s ) + H 2 O ( g ) → CO ( g ) + H 2( g )

explanation.concept_text: Le Chatelier’s principle states that the equilibrium point will be shifted in response to a change in temperature or concentration that disturbs the original dynamic equilibrium. A change in pressure will affect the equilibrium point if the number of moles of gas in the reactants is different than in the products. An increase in pressure will cause the equilibrium to shift to the side that has fewer moles of gas, and a decrease in pressure will cause the equilibrium to shift to the side that has greater moles of gas.  Therefore, the equilibrium point of Option E. CS 2(l) + 3 O 2(g) → CO 2(g) +2 SO 2(g) will NOT be affected by a change in pressure because there are 3 moles of gas on both sides of the reaction, making it the correct answer. Canadian DAT Pro-Tip: An increase in temperature will cause the equilibrium to shift toward the side that absorbs heat. A decrease in temperature causes the equilibrium to shift toward the side that produces heat. For example: CC By 4.0
explanation.poe_text: Option A. Li 2 S (aq) + HBr (aq) → 2 LiBr (aq) + H 2 S (g) – This is incorrect because there is zero moles of gas on the left side and one mole of gas on the right side. An increase in pressure will shift the equilibrium to the left and a decrease in pressure will shift it to the right. Option B. 2 H 2(g) + O 2(g) → 2 H 2 O (g) – This is incorrect because there are three moles of gas on the left side and two moles of gas on the right side. An increase in pressure will shift the equilibrium to the right and a decrease in pressure will shift it to the left. Option C. 2 Na (s) + Cl 2(g) → 2 NaCl (s) – This is incorrect because there is one mole of gas on the left side and zero moles of gas on the right side. An increase in pressure will shift the equilibrium to the right and a decrease in pressure will shift it to the left. Option D. C (s) + H 2 O (g) → CO (g) + H 2(g) – This is incorrect because there is one mole of gas on the left side and two moles of gas on the right side. An increase in pressure will shift the equilibrium to the left and a decrease in pressure will shift it to the right.
